                "Title": "Vision",
                "Content": "Where should the first hammerstroke fall?<br>As Xilonen gripped the haft, preparing to get started on the first Ancient Name she had ever forged, she hesitated, unsure of how to strike.<br>She had done plenty of research and prepared everything that was required. Just a few days before, she had followed a mining team from the tribe into the mountains to find ore of the very finest quality. She had also asked her dad to modify the furnace so it could hold even more phlogiston, igniting a fiercer and hotter flame that would be intense enough to melt any ore. She had specially re-engraved all of the phlogiston engraving diagrams in the workshop, ensuring that every spark that flew during the forging process was under her complete control.<br>Alright, Xilonen, everything's ready. Strike while the phlogiston's hot, huh? So... Where should the first strike fall? What pattern should I forge? How many strikes will it take?<br>Silence filled the workshop, and even the flames dared not crackle, lest they disturb the craftswoman at work.<br>Placing her hammer aside, Xilonen picked up a comb fashioned from the tooth of a wild beast in its stead. This comb had been polished sleek and smooth, investing the intense fire that reflected off its surface with a mild, gentler warmth.<br>Its previous owner was a kindly old woman. Whenever Xilonen used to slack off, she would offer to comb her hair as a way of coaxing her back to study.<br>The old woman would also braid her hair into beautiful, intricate plaits — so complex, in fact, that even Xilonen's mother could not work out how to recreate them, and eventually had to ask for her help. After all, above all others, those were the plaits that Xilonen loved.<br>The story of Teyiz the Name Engraver resurfaced in Xilonen's mind. That was a story she had hunted down and gathered herself; and now, she would be the one to forge it into a Name.<br>A hammer blow shattered the silence. Each strike was precise and powerful, and no detail of the story was left untold. Even the most fleeting nuances now rose up before her, ready to be wrought by her hammer.<br>As the final drops of phlogiston were consumed and the furnace began to fade, before her she beheld a brand-new Ancient Name.<br>Teyiz's story had been imprinted into this Name, never to be distorted again.<br>As for whom the Wayob would bestow it upon... Well, that was the Wayob's concern, not hers.<br>Xilonen stood up, dusted off her clothes, and began to tidy up her workshop. She bent down to toss away a few unused pieces of ore into a basket — they were all of excellent quality, and could certainly be re-used for something else.<br>\"Hmm, wonder what I should eat later? Didn't Mom say we'd be having fish for dinner...?\"<br>One, two, three... the lumps of ore clinked as they landed in her basket.<br>Absorbed entirely by her dinner plans, Xilonen didn't notice that there was something quite special about the fourth, amber-colored \"ore\" in her hand.<br>With another soft clink, the Vision landed in her basket too, which Xilonen then carried out of the workshop and casually left outside.<br>Humming a song, Xilonen went off to eat her dinner. It was only during her next forging session that she would finally notice this special \"ore\" of hers.<br>It was a gift; but also, a responsibility.",
